  We study the effect of increased flexibility--increasing the number of
actions available to an agent--on an agent's value for information. Adding a
single action makes information more valuable if and only if the new action is
either weakly dominated or extremal, i.e., a (partial) substitute for at most
one action. This result extends naturally to the situation in which multiple
new actions are made available to the agent. We apply these findings to a
monopolistic screening problem in which the good is information and to
delegation with information acquisition.
